thread.title: No. 1 Middletown South blasts Freehold Township
thread.title_full: No. 1 Middletown South blasts Freehold Township

author: app.com
title: No. 1 Middletown South blasts Freehold Township
text:
MORE FREEHOLD TOWNSHIP It looked easy when Middletown South junior wide receiver Samson Dube on a 9 route caught a touchdown pass from Matt Mosquera against Freehold Township Saturday, but Dube said practice makes perfect.
“We practice hard, watch a lot of film, and make sure we do what we have to do to win,’’ Dube said after the No. 1 Eagles won 42-0 to remain the only undefeated Shore Conference Class A North team.
The 29-yard play in the second quarter was one of two Mosquera to Dube touchdowns, and Mosquera added a third scoring pass to Tom Coffey on a 31-yard play later in the second quarter. Mosquera completed 5 of 8 passes for 78 yards.
Most of the other scoring came courtesy of the defense and special teams.
Maxx Imsho opened the scoring for Middletown South (4-0, 2-0) with a 67-yard interception pick 6, Coffey made an interception that set up Dube’s 10-yard touchdown catch in the first quarter, and Tom Marron scored on kickoff overage when he scooped up a fumble by Freehold Township (1-3, 1-3) and returned it 30 yards.
“A great effort defensively,’’ said Middletown South coach Steve Antonucci. “Plus we scored on special teams. I tell the kids, if we’re going to win championships, the bottom line is we have to be good at all three facets of the game. If we can do that, we have a good chance for success.’’
All this came as the Eagles’ feature back, Cole Rogers, was sidelined by an injury for the second straight game.
The Rogers void was filled by junior James McCarthy, who rushed 17 times for 135 yards and capped the scoring with a five-yard run in the third quarter.
“It’s great to have him in the No. 2 spot while your No. 1 is trying to heal up,’’ Antonucci said of McCarthy. “We hope to get Cole back next week and get him into the flow.’’
Heavy rains, which continued through the game, left the field both bumpy and muddy, but Dube said, “We actually have a back practice field that gets pretty muddy and sometimes we practice there for a grass field game. So we knew what to expect.’’
Antonucci said the Eagles made the most of the conditions.
“It was like backyard football. You get muddy, you get sloppy, but you have a good time doing it,’’ he said.
Key play: Middletown South’s first two drives ended in punts but Maxx Imsho provided the spark with a 67-yard pick 6 in the first quarter.
Offensive game ball: Eagles’ junior James McCarthy rushed for 135 yards with a touchdown.
Defensive game ball: Tom Coffey of Middletown South had an interception and a fumble recovery.
Up next: Freehold Township hosts Toms River East and Middletown South hosts Howell Friday.
